
This tutorial describes the steps to create a virtual drive on Linux server using MDADM

My setup details:
        
        Centos 7.1

Procedure:
  1)  For Centos, YUM is the default package manager. Using yum, install mdadm package
     yum -y install mdadm
     
  2)  For the purpose of creating virtual drive, I mounted two extra disks. My goal is to create a RAID 0 virtual drive using these two disks
      Disk 1 - 25G
      Disk 2 - 25G
      
  3) Create a disk partition on both disks using fdisk
    
  4) Create the virtual drive
      mdadm --create /dev/md007 --level 0 --raid-devices 2 /dev/sdc1 /dev/sdd1 
   
  5) Create the filesystem 
      mkfs.ext4 -t ext4 /dev/md007
    
  6) Create the directory. In my case, I want to mount my 50G space under /data
      mkdir -p /data
    
  7) To ensure, /data gets mounted even after a server reboot update the fstab. Using blkid, find the UUID of above filesystem and update fstab
      UUID=abcde  /data  ext4  defaults  0  2
    
  8) Finally mount 
      mount -a
